<subSubSection id="88AD959AFFCC4E04FF5AFD59FA9CFBF3" pageId="30" pageNumber="281" type="description">
<paragraph id="C008C611FFCC4E04FF5AFD59FA9CFBF3" blockId="30.[151,1436,750,1099]" pageId="30" pageNumber="281">
<emphasis id="F2C31A03FFCC4E04FF5AFD59FEF2FCBF" bold="true" box="[151,299,750,775]" pageId="30" pageNumber="281">Description:</emphasis>
This group currently includes a single species in the Palaearctic region, 
<taxonomicName id="07B7BD92FFCC4E04FBBAFD58FAF9FCBF" box="[1143,1312,750,775]" class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Megachile" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="30" pageNumber="281" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="riyadhensis">
<emphasis id="F2C31A03FFCC4E04FBBAFD58FAF9FCBF" box="[1143,1312,750,775]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="281">M. riyadhensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(see notes about the identity of this species below). It possesses a few unique characteristics: in the female, the particularly enlarged apicomedial protuberance of the clypeus (
<figureCitation id="588CDA94FFCC4E04FD14FC81FCF2FCF7" box="[729,811,822,847]" captionStart="FIGURES 6–21" captionStartId="10.[151,264,1876,1899]" captionTargetBox="[164,1421,292,1841]" captionTargetId="figure@10.[164,1421,292,1841]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURES 6–21. Clypeus and mandibles of females. 6: M. foersteri. 7: M. incana. 8: M. blepharis sp. nov.. 9: M. cinnamomea. 10: M. saussurei. 11: M. nigripes. 12: M. seraxensis. 13: M. ericetorum. 14: M. sanguinipes. 15 (hairs removed on left): M. maxschwarzi sp. nov.. 16 (hairs removed on left): M. flavipes. 17 (hairs removed on left): M. tecta. 18: M. cinnamomea. 19, 20 (profile): M. farinosa. 21: M. riyadhensis (profile). CT: clypeal tooth, APA: apical premarginal area of mandible, HT: clypeal hair tuft, FC: facial comb of hairs." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2610532/files/figure.png" pageId="30" pageNumber="281">Fig. 21</figureCitation>
) is possibly homologous to the much smaller preapical medial protuberance found in both the 
<taxonomicName id="07B7BD92FFCC4E04FD98FCEBFD02FCCB" authorityName="Guerin-Meneville" authorityYear="1845" box="[597,731,860,883]" class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Megachile" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="30" pageNumber="281" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cyanipennis">
<emphasis id="F2C31A03FFCC4E04FD98FCEBFD02FCCB" box="[597,731,860,883]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="281">cyanipennis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="07B7BD92FFCC4E04FCD9FCEBFCB9FCCB" authorityName="Friese" authorityYear="1898" box="[788,864,860,883]" class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Megachile" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="30" pageNumber="281" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="incana">
<emphasis id="F2C31A03FFCC4E04FCD9FCEBFCB9FCCB" box="[788,864,860,883]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="281">incana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species groups; and the mandible with four sharp teeth. In the male, the reduced, inconspicuous front coxal spine appears to build a transition between the 
<taxonomicName id="07B7BD92FFCC4E04FA9DFCC8FA45FC2E" authorityName="Friese" authorityYear="1898" box="[1360,1436,895,918]" class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Megachile" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="30" pageNumber="281" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="incana">
<emphasis id="F2C31A03FFCC4E04FA9DFCC8FA45FC2E" box="[1360,1436,895,918]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="281">incana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="07B7BD92FFCC4E04FF0BFC13FE95FC03" authorityName="Guerin-Meneville" authorityYear="1845" box="[198,332,932,955]" class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Megachile" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="30" pageNumber="281" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cyanipennis">
<emphasis id="F2C31A03FFCC4E04FF0BFC13FE95FC03" box="[198,332,932,955]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="281">cyanipennis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species groups (
<tableCitation id="8D35F3AAFFCC4E04FDC9FC15FD8EFC03" box="[516,599,930,955]" captionStart="TABLE 1" captionStartId="5.[147,224,663,683]" captionText="TABLE 1. Main diagnostic traits of recognized species and species groups of the subgenus Pseudomegachile in the western Palaearctic." pageId="30" pageNumber="281">Table 1</tableCitation>
); sternites 5 and 6 of the male are unlike that of any other species (Figs 93, 94), although S 
<date id="B409E0D1FFCC4E04FE88FC71FE55FC67" box="[325,396,966,991]" pageId="30" pageNumber="281">5 may</date>
also be interpreted as intermediate between the two latter groups. Additionally, in the male the light front basitarsus with a conspicuous ventral dark spot is shared with the 
<taxonomicName id="07B7BD92FFCC4E04FBEAFC5BFB74FBBB" authorityName="Guerin-Meneville" authorityYear="1845" box="[1063,1197,1004,1027]" class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Megachile" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="30" pageNumber="281" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cyanipennis">
<emphasis id="F2C31A03FFCC4E04FBEAFC5BFB74FBBB" box="[1063,1197,1004,1027]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="281">cyanipennis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species group, while the absence of inferior mandibular projection is shared with the 
<taxonomicName id="07B7BD92FFCC4E04FCA8FBB8FC6BFB9E" authorityName="Friese" authorityYear="1898" box="[869,946,1039,1062]" class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Megachile" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="30" pageNumber="281" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="incana">
<emphasis id="F2C31A03FFCC4E04FCA8FBB8FC6BFB9E" box="[869,946,1039,1062]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="281">incana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species group. Finally, the apical margin of T7 has a deep emargination, a unique character within Palaearctic and Arabian 
<taxonomicName id="07B7BD92FFCC4E04FBC2FB85FB0CFBF3" authorityName="Friese" authorityYear="1898" box="[1039,1237,1074,1099]" class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Megachile" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="30" pageNumber="270" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subGenus" subGenus="Pseudomegachile">
<emphasis id="F2C31A03FFCC4E04FBC2FB85FB0CFBF3" box="[1039,1237,1074,1099]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="281">Pseudomegachile</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation id="588CDA94FFCC4E04FB2EFB85FAE1FBF3" box="[1251,1336,1074,1099]" captionStart="FIGURES 22–37" captionStartId="11.[151,264,1491,1514]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,193,1470]" captionTargetId="figure@11.[151,1436,193,1470]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="FIGURES 22–37. Diagnostic traits of males. 22: inferior mandibular projection of M. nigripes. Anterior coxal spine of 23: M. nigripes, 24: M. lanata. Front legs of males of 25: M. foersteri (anterior surface), 26: M. cyanipennis (anterior surface), 27: M. ericetorum (ventral surface), 28: M. cinnamomea (ventral surface), 29: M. cyanipennis (ventral surface), 30: M. cinnamomea (dorsal surface), 31: M. farinosa (dorsal surface). T6 and T7 of 32: M. farinosa, 33: M. cinnamomea, 34: M. lanata, 35: M. seraxensis, 36: M. schnabli, 37: M. riyadhensis. IBP: inferior basal projection, ACS: anterior coxal spine, AG: anterior groove, BAM: basitarsal anterior margin, MPS: minute posterior spot, PAC: preapical carina, LS: lateral spine." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2610536/files/figure.png" pageId="30" pageNumber="281">Fig. 37</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
